The absorption spectrum of the free Schiff base ligand exhibits bands at 219, 273 and 342 nm, which are red-shifted in the lanthanide complexes (Figure S5). The free H2L ligand displays a visible emission at 618 nm (λex = 406 nm) (Figure S6). Upon the excitation of ligand absorption bands, 1 and 2 exhibit the visible ligand-centered emission and NIR lanthanide luminescence of Yb(III) (2F5/2 → 2F7/2 transition) and Nd(III) (4F3/2→4Ij/2 transitions, j = 9, 11 and 13) (Fig. 4
                        ) in CH3CN, while their solid lanthanide luminescence is not obvious under the same experimental conditions. The NIR photoluminescence data of 1 and 2 in CH3CN are shown in Table 1
                        . The lanthanide luminescence lifetimes (τ) of 1 and 2 are 14.12 μs and 6.78 μs (Figure S7), respectively. Thus, the intrinsic quantum yields (ΦLn) of Yb(III) and Nd(III) are calculated to be 0.7% and 2.7%, respectively [28].

The quenching mechanism of Que to the emissions of 2 was studied by some experiments such as PXRD, UV–vis absorption spectra, and luminescence lifetimes. The recycled sample of 2 after the sensing experiments of Que shows similar PXRD pattern to that before the experiments (Figure S9), indicating that the Nd(III) nanocluster is stable during the experiments. Thus, the quenching of the emissions of 2 is not caused by the decomposition of the cluster. In 2, L2− ligands can absorb and transfer light energy to lanthanide ions (“antenna effect”, Scheme 2
                        ), resulting in the Nd(III) emission [35]. Que has a much higher absorption coefficient at λex = 367 nm than 2 (1.13 × 105 M−1cm−1 
                        vs. 0.19 × 105 M−1cm−1, Fig. 10
                        ). Thus, Que can effectively compete with 2 for the absorption of light energy at λex, leading to the luminescence quenching (“inner filter effect”, Scheme 2) [36,37]. Upon the excitation at 367 nm, Que does not display emission at about 514 nm. Not surprisingly, due to the decrease of excitation energy of 2, its visible ligand-centered emission is also quenched with the addition of Que. Unlike Que, these interferents do not show high absorption at λex (Fig. 10).
